itney, Oxfordshire, England":"Witney, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1377–":"circa 1377–Overleden","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1395–1465":"1395–1465","1377–Female":"1377–Overleden","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1465":"1465","Abt 1375":"circa 1395","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","about 1377":"circa 1377","1382":"1382","Witney, Oxfordshire, England":"Witney, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1377–":"about 1377–Deceased","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1395–1465":"1395–1465","1377–Female":"1377–Deceased","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1465":"1465","Abt 1375":"about 1395","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","about 1377":"about 1377","1382":"1382","Witney, Oxfordshire, England":"Witney, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fermour","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Farmer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Farmer","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>fermo(u)r</i>, <i>fermer</i> and Anglo-Norman French <i>fermer</i> (Old French <i>fermier</i>, medieval Latin <i>firmarius</i>). The term denoted in the first instance a tax farmer, one who undertook the collection of taxes, revenues, and imposts, paying a fixed (Latin <i>firmus</i>) sum for the proceeds, and only secondarily someone who rented land for the purpose of cultivation; it was not applied to an owner of cultivated land before the 17th century.","Irish: Anglicized (part translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Scolóige</b> ‘son of the husbandman’, a rare surname of northern and western Ireland.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Terrien   ‘owner of a farmland’ or of its altered form   Therrien  . Compare   Pharmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":78,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Agnes Fermour was born about 1377, in England. She married Thomas Fermore in 1394. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1377–":"umbes 1377–Surnud","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1395–1465":"1395–1465","1377–Female":"1377–Surnud","1415"